The aim of this project is for Save the Children to support the development and implementation of advocacy strategies in 3 countries (Burkina Faso, Mali and Senegal) that successfully influence decision-makers to take concrete steps to put into practice the health financing reforms required to move closer to universal coverage.

Save the Children's  Early Childhood Care and Development (ECCD) programme enrols approximately 10,000 children aged 3-6 across all refugee camps. All of SC's ECCD centres include Water Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH) promotion initiatives as core components of the curriculum thereby using education as a platform for wider live changing services.

This five-year project will improve the development and survival of children under five in Brazil and Peru as a strategy for poverty reduction in both countries. The action will empower the community and build the capacity of non-state actors and local authorities to make service provision more equitable and efficient. The action will target 132,000 of the most vulnerable children including indigenous children and children from African descent.
Child protection and education work in a refugee camp and six of its host villages as well as in Transit Centres and Way Stations in Liberia.

ECHO wishes to roll out the Minimum Reporting Package (MRP) to multiple implementing agencies to improve the systematisation and quality of monitoring data of emergency  Supplementary Feeding  Programmes (SFP) it funds under emergency decisions. ECHO seeks the partnership of Save the Children UK to facilitate this.

Finding innovative solutions to tackle the depth and extent of chronic food insecurity, poverty and vulnerability. Save the Children, in consortium with two other Non-Governmental Organisations, will be responsible for the targeting and identification of beneficiaries (the "Administration" component of the Hunger Safety Net Programme).

DFID is seeking proposals from research and academic institutions to plan, manage and implement an operational research and impact evaluation (ORIE) component of a large programme to tackle undernutrition in Northern Nigeria. The programme will be implemented across 5 states, over 6 years and focuses on scaling up direct nutrition interventions known to be effective in tackling undernutrition and reducing mortality. The ORIE component would work closely with those implementing the programme, and also link with DFID funded research programmes in Nutrition. In addition, the selected supplier will be responsible for tracking and coordinating progress reports from all the implementing partners delivering programme outputs, for onward transmission to DFID.

In recognition of the fact that a significant proportion of the households in the target locations, just like the rest of South Sudan live beyond the reach of health facilities, resulting in sick children being brought late to the facility or not at all, the integrated Community Case Management (iCCM) is designed to avail curative services at the community level. The project will focus on assessment, classification, and treatment of malaria, pneumonia and diarrhoea amongst children aged 2-59 months at the community level with referral of severe cases to the nearest health facility.

Save the Children already works in several of the areas most affected by the recent flooding in Thailand. In August -September, partners working with stateless children and families were supported to repair water pipes, transport school children in areas where bridges were destroyed, to carry out repair of seriously damaged houses, and deliver food and non-food aid. Given the urgency of the flooding in the central plains, using internal funds, Save the Children quickly launched an initial stage of its response helping set up systems in evacuation centres, establishing child friendly spaces, and child safeguarding structures in the first week of the onset of the disaster.

In order to respond to the increasingly complex situation, Save the Children Canada and the Norwegian Refugee Council have prepared a joint intervention designed to further the right to quality and inclusive formal and non-formal education for the displaced.
